Emilio Rivera, American actor.

@emiliorivera48 shares his struggle with addiction and recovery in the hope that it will help others. He grew up in a rough neighborhood in L.A where domestic violence and gang wars were the norm.

Drugs made Emilio feel indestructible, and also helped him deal with what we now call ADHD. It was not widely understood when he was young, but it had a big impact on his life.

Emilio managed to get through high school because he had a deal with the principal. He could stay in school in spite of his grades, if he would mediate the gang conflicts. This often meant he fought the gang rivals himself.

Emilio describes himself as a functional addict. He worked and held a job because that was a family tradition to take care of the family, but he liked drugs and nice clothes. His health declined, as did his relationships.

A turning point came one evening when a friend, Ernie Aguirre showed up at his home. Aguirre, who had been sober for five years, insisted that Emilio join him at a group meeting.

Emilio was focused only on scoring his next high, and kept trying to get around the guy so he could leave. But the friend stayed for hours. Finally, Emilio gave in and agreed to attend the meeting.

It was in a rough part of east Los Angeles, and when they entered the room, Emilio said it looked like a gang convention. He thought they were planning to kill him.

Soon the meeting began, and Emilio stood stiffly against the back wall listening. One by one the guys shared their stories. The details of each were different, but they were telling his story as well. It changed his life, and he quit drugs cold turkey.
Support meetings became a lifeline for him.

On May 15, 2022, Emilio marked an impressive 32 years of sobriety. He will tell you that sobriety takes work, but it also makes you less selfish. You step up and take responsibility, you give back to your community, and you make a difference in the world. Each day is an amazing gift to be celebrated.

Credit: Ernie Aguirre saved Emilios life twice , first time when Emilio OD'd and second time when he helped him get sober.

We are delighted to introduce Emilio Rivera as the Padrino de Honor for the upcoming LEAD XII Summit. His life story is a testament to resilience and transformation, making him a true beacon of hope.

Born in San Antonio, Texas, Emilio grew up in the challenging environment of Elysian Valley, Los Angeles, known as Frogtown. Despite facing numerous obstacles, including the lure of street life and gangs, he enlisted in the US Army after high school. However, the journey towards his true calling was far from linear.

Emilio's path initially led him down a road of self-destruction, marked by association with street gangs, substance abuse, and reckless behavior. It was during a pivotal moment of his life that acting emerged as his lifeline. Emilio sought help, went through rehab, and embarked on a journey of self-discovery through acting.

Starting as a stage actor and honing his craft in comedy clubs, Emilio discovered his true passion. The discipline and dedication he poured into acting transformed his life in remarkable ways. He transitioned from mechanical engineering to pursue his dream, defying the odds.

With an impressive portfolio of nearly 150 acting credits, Emilio Rivera is celebrated for his authenticity and compelling presence on screen. He gained international recognition for his portrayal of Marcus Álvarez, the fearless leader of the Mayans Oakland charter, in the hit FX series Sons of Anarchy and its spin-off, Mayans M.C.

Notably, the character Marcus Álvarez is referred to as "El Padrino" by his fellow Mayans, a title of immense respect. In a remarkable twist of life imitating art, our LEAD Projects bestow this title upon Mr. Rivera as a symbol of honor and inspiration.

Emilio's journey embodies the essence of transformation and the pursuit of dreams against all odds. We are excited to have him as the Padrino de Honor at LEAD XII Summit, where his story will undoubtedly motivate and empower us all.
